<p>Tanzania’s climate is equatorial and mostly tropical. Coastal areas are usually hot and humid, but a light sea breeze cools the air on the beaches.
<p>Tanzania has two rainy seasons: the long rainy season from March up to the end of May and a short rainy season between November and mid December. The hottest period is from December to March, the coolest months are June, July and August. On high-altitude regions, like Kilimanjaro and Ngorongoro Crater highlands, temperatures can fall below freezing.

<h4>Which season is best for your safari trip?</h4>
<p>The best time to travel depends on the region you want to visit and the animals you wish to spot. Some reserves have a good game viewing all the year. Others offer less viewing opportunities if visited during the dry season.

<p><strong><em>Northern Circuit (Serengeti, Ngorongoro, Tarangire, Manyara, Arusha)</em></strong><br>
These National parks are recommended for year round visits, including the the rainy season. In the dry season (July – October) animals are concentrated around water reservoirs. The grass is shorter and the animals are more easily seen, as well as the hunting activities. From November to June the land is greener and the grass is longer.

<p><strong><em>Southern Circuit (Selous, Ruaha) </em></strong><br>
The best time to visit is during the dry season, from July to the end of October. During the rainy season it’s more difficult to spot animals in the wide open plains.</p>